    <text>
        <body>
            <div style="handwritten" type="letter">
                <head type="title">Camillo Ghilino to Miklós Oláh (Milan, 12 August 1534)</head>
                <floatingText type="regesta">
                    <body>
                        <p>Since
                            <?oxy_custom_start type="oxy_content_highlight" color="255,255,0"?>count
                            Maximilian’s<?oxy_custom_end?> men have arrived to buy a gyrfalcon,
                            Ghilino is taking the opportunity to write to Oláh. The Empress suffered
                            a stillbirth, which has saddened everyone. The Pope is suffering from
                            dysentery, and the physicians have given up on him, even if he is
                            somewhat better now. Hayreddin Barbarossa Pasha is said to be heading
                            for Malta. They have learned from a letter from Sicily that King Francis
                            I has sent Antonio Rincon to the Turks, and that the Sultan’s envoy
                            suffered a shipwreck on his way home and has been captured, but he has
                            been ransomed. Lodovico Gritti has arrived to Belgrade to mediate
                            between King Ferdinand I and Szapolyai, he wishes he was successful. He
                            would like to hear about the English affairs.</p>
                    </body>
                </floatingText>
                <pb/>
                <p>Idem Nicolao Olao salutem.</p>
                <pb/>
                <p>Scripsi superioribus diebus ad te de omnibus rebus, quae hic
                    circumferebantur et litteris tuis, quas ad me <persName>Candiano</persName><note
                        type="critic">Ambrogio Candiano.</note> dedisti, respondi.<note
                        type="critic">Probably Ep. 490. and Ep.
                        491.</note><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15340531_1</ref><ref>/o:olahus.tei.15340531_2</ref>
                    Nunc venientibus istuc Maximiliani comitis familiaribus emptum hirifalcos<note
                        type="critic">The gyrfalcon according to Hoven, i.e. the largest of the
                        falcon species (falco rusticolus). See <hi rend="smallcap">Hoven</hi> 2006,
                        246.</note> non falcones, officii mei esse censui haec paucula tibi exarare,
                    quo meam sempiternam erga te observantiam facilius cognoscere posses.
                        <persName>Augustae</persName><note type="critic">Isabella of
                        Portugal.</note> abortus<note type="critic">This son was stillborn. The
                        Empress had seven pregnancies and suffered two miscarriages.</note> nos
                    omnes sollicitos reddidit. Utinam caesari in danda filiis opera melior ei
                    fortuna arrideat, sed deos spero caesari, deo nostro<note type="critic">After
                        this word, a word missing.</note> fore propitios.
                        <persName>Pontifex</persName><note type="critic">Pope Clement VII.</note> ex
                    Urbanis litteris III. Nonarum Sextilis<note type="critic">3 August.</note>
                    disenteria gravissime laborabat, hominem medici in desperatis habebant, quamvis
                    meliusculus esset factus.<note type="critic">Indeed, he died soon, on 25
                        September.</note>
                    <persName>Aenobarbus</persName><note type="critic">Hayreddin Barbarossa
                        Pasha.</note> cum classe Turcica <placeName>Zaznithum</placeName> versus
                    navigabat oppugnaturus <placeName>Melitam</placeName><note type="critic"
                        >Malta.</note> incerto tamen rumore. Ex <persName>Siculis</persName>
                    litteris nobis nuntiatum est <persName>Gallum</persName><note type="critic">King
                        Francis I.</note> misisse ad Turcas Rineonem<note type="critic">Antonio
                        Rincon (†1541) was an envoy of King Francis I to Szapolyai, later to Sultan
                        Suleiman I and he was sent to Constantinople between 1530 and 1541 several
                        times, see <hi rend="smallcap">Setton</hi> 1984, passim; and <hi
                            rend="smallcap">Kasza</hi> 2015, 91–92 and 156.</note> Hispanum. Item
                    Turcae oratorem redeuntem ex Gallia naufragium fecisse in sirtibus minoribus
                    captum et postea redemptum ad caesarem suum profectum. Audivimus
                        <persName>Gritteum</persName><note type="critic">Lodovico Gritti.</note>
                    <placeName>Albam Graecam</placeName><note type="critic">Belgrade.</note>
                    pervenisse pro componendis inter <persName>regem</persName><note type="critic"
                        >King Ferdinand I.</note> nostrum et <persName>Ioannem</persName><note
                        type="critic">King John I.</note> rebus. Utinam ex sententia nostra, quod
                    reliquum est, succedat. Ego de Anglicis rebus certior fieri cupio.
                        <persName>Rimoldus</persName><note type="critic">We do not know him more
                        closely.</note> operam suam tibi praestabit, quo me possis rariora et
                    constantissima docere. Salutabis meo nomine clarissimam <persName>Virginem
                        Lucretiam</persName>.<note type="critic">Lucretia Caballis (vom
                        Ross).</note> Valere cupio Olaum meum et serenissimae dominae, dominae
                    reginae, dominae nostrae clementissimae pedes deosculor. Vale, Amicorum Optime,
                    et <persName>Bannisio</persName><note type="critic">Jakob Radich de Bannisis the
                        Younger.</note> me commenda, cui et in primis tibi globum meum curae esse
                    cupio. Si <persName>Rotterodamus</persName> noster in patriam rediit, fac, ex te
                    intelligam. </p>
                <p><placeName>Mediolano</placeName> pridie Idus Sextilis 1534.</p>
            </div>
        </body>
